description.undefined: Module for dialogue process and system output management.

title.value: TODODM: Dialogue Management Module for Task-Oriented Dialogue management Ontology (TODO)

comment.undefined: Marker that establishes that the dialogue must be finished.

example.value: Ask for missing information, ask for confirmation.

comment.en: Act in which the system requires user input.

comment.undefined: Step Function associated to a ContentRequest.
Marker that requires the dialogue to restart.

example.value:
"Hi! I am {SystemName}. I am happy to help you."

"Hi! I am {Teknibot}. I am happy to help you."

"¡Hola! Soy {SystemName}. Encantado de ayudarte."

"¡Hola! Soy {Teknibot}. Encantado de ayudarte."

comment.en: Welcome message.

example.value: ¡Tu comando se puede asociar a demasiados argumentos! ¿Puedes repetir y ser un poco más específico, por favor?
Your command can be associated to too many arguments! Can you repeat and be more specific, please?
Response given when the number of possible Arguments is too big.

comment.undefined: Step Function associated to a YesNoRequest.

example.value: Which is the error code?

comment.en:
Request that asks for specific information, other than "Yes" or "No" (and equivalents).

Also known as "Non polar/Open question" in linguistics.

comment.undefined: Step in the dialogue process that does not require a system interaction with the user (SystemStep).

example.value:
"The {Argument} corresponds to {ArgDescription}"

"The {Error} corresponds to {the ID of the error that appears in the machine}"

"El {Argument} corresponde a{ArgDescription}"

"El {Error} corresponde a{l número de error que aparece en la máquina}"

comment.en: Response that gives details about an Argument. For example, when the user does not understand what information conveys said Argument.

example.value:
"¿Puedes decirme el {argument}?"

"¿Puedes decirme el {Destino}?"

"Can you tell me the {argument}?

"Can you tell me the {Destination}?"

comment.en: Request that demands for the value of an Argument.

comment.undefined: Step performed by the system in order to request information to the user or simply outputting information.

comment.en: Reponse given to the user when the UserResponse is a ContentResponse and the SystemRequest requires a YesNoResponse.
comment.es: "Solo necesito que me digas sí o no, por favor"

example.value: I cannot find anything that corresponds to your demand.
No encuentro ningún elemento que responda a lo que me pides.

comment.en: Response that the system returns when the clarification step of the value of an Argument does not return any results.

comment.undefined: Marker that conveys the idea of continuing with the dialogue process.

example.value:
"Can you repeat the {Argument}?

"Can you repeat the {Destination}?"

"¿Puedes repetir el {argument}?"

"¿Puedes repetir el {Destino}?"

comment.en: Request that demands the user to repeat the value of an Argument.

comment.undefined: Step Function associated to a ProcessStep.

example.value:
"¿De qué {characteristic} es {too_broad_argument}?

"¿De qué {color} es (la) {pieza}?"

"Which {characteristic} is {too_broad_argument}?"

"Which {colour} is (the) {piece}?"

comment.en:
Request that demands a specific characteristic of the argument. This request is used when the argument provided is too broad and the system needs some characteristic that allows determining the specific element the user is refering to.

For example, the user would require a "piece", and the system includes data for 300 types of pieces.

example.value:
"Do you want {Action} {ArgumentConnector} {WorldElement}?"

"Do you want {to go} {to} {Sala Ura}?"

"¿Quieres {Action} {ArgumentConnector} {WorldElement}?"

"¿Quieres {que te guíe} {a} {Sala Ura}?"

comment.en: Request that tries to obtain the value of the argument when it is ambiguous (e.g. "sala" may apply to "sala Ura", "sala Sua", etc.).

example.value: "I have many options for your request."

"Tengo varias opciones para tu comando."

"¡Lo que me has dicho puede ser varias cosas!"

comment.en:
Response in which the system tells the user that it has several options for a specific element (e.g. WorldElement).

Note the difference between OptionsAvailableResponse and TooManyAlternativesResponse: the first implies that there is a fair amount of options, whereas the latter implies that the options that are available are too many and it will require the user to be more specific.

example.value:
"¿Puedes ser un poco más específico con el {ArgTag}?"

"¿Puedes ser un poco más específico con el {destino al que quieres que te guíe}?"

"Could you please be more specific with {ArgTag}?"

"Could you please be more specific with {the destination you want me to take you}?"

comment.en: Request that asks the user for some clarification for the value of an argument when a previously saved value generates too many options.

example.value:
"{ArgumentValue} no puede ser {Argument}."

"{Baño} no puede ser {Error}."

"{ArgumentValue} cannot be the {Argument}."

"{Toilet} cannot be the {Error}."

comment.en: The system informs the user the Argument value provided is not valid according to what has been modelled in the KB.

example.value:
Request: "Llévame a un laboratorio con micrófono".

"No encuentro ningún/a {Item} con {Complement} como {argumentTag}, pero puedo sugerir {IDval_AlternativeItem}, que sí que tiene. ¿Le llevo ahí?"

"No encuentro ningún/a {laboratorio} con {micrófono} como {el destino al que quiere que le lleve}, pero puedo sugerir {sala de reunión 1}, que sí que tiene. ¿Le llevo ahí?"

Request: "Take me to a laboratory with microphone".

"I cannot find any {Item} with {Complement} as {ArgumentTag}, but I can suggest {IDval_AlternativeItem}, which it does have it. Do you want me to take you there?"

"I cannot find any {laboratory} with {microphone} as {the destination you want to go}, but I can suggest {meeting room 1}, which it does have it. Do you want me to take you there?"

comment.es: Request that arises when the system has not been able to obtain an argument through an item + complement. The system suggests an alternative that contains the complement in the request.

example.value:
"It cannot be the {Argument}".

"It cannot be the {destination you want me to take you}".

"No puede ser {Argument}".

"No puede ser {el lugar al que quieres que te lleve}".

comment.en: Response given when the ArgValue for an Argument provided by the user is not compatible with said Argument.

example.value:
[Situation: the value "Mesa de reparación" could be Origin or Destination]

[Previous SysResponse: "¡Lo que me has dicho podría ser varias cosas!"]

"¿Es {el lugar al que quieres que te lleve}?"

"¿Es {Argument}?"

[Situation: the value "Repairing table" could be Origin or Destination]

[Previous SysResponse: "What you told me could correspond to many elements!"]

"Is it {the place you want me to take you}?"

"Is it {Argument}?"

comment.en: Request made when a value for an Argument can belong to different Arguments. The strategy is asking for each Argument option until the user confirms.

example.value: I couldn't associate your command to an action. Can you please be more specific?
No he podido asociar tu comando a una acción. ¿Puedes repetir y ser más específico, por favor?

comment.en: Response that the system gives when it cannot associate an action/target to one or more actions.

example.value: I could not resolve your command.
No he podido resolver tu petición.

comment.en:
Response that informs the user that the command could not be resolved.

[to be followed by an ArgRequest]

example.value: Your command can be associated to many actions!
¡El comando puede asociarse a varias acciones!

comment.en: Response that the system gives when a command can be associated to more than one action.
Information that the system provides in response to a UserRequest or as a piece of information directed to the user without a prior UserRequest.

example.value: I do not have more options to offer you! Can you reformulate your command so I can understand better?
¡No tengo más opciones que mostrarte! ¿Puedes reformular tu comando para que te entienda mejor?

comment.en: Response that the system displays when it runs out of options. It finishes the current Dialogue.

example.value: Continue, restart dialogue

comment.undefined: Elements that correspond to predefined or generic actions in dialogue control.
Response given by the system to reassure the user that it has understood the request.

example.value:
"Have I missed the {Argument}?"

"Have I missed the {Origin}?"

"¿Me he equivocado con el {Argument}?"

"¿Me he equivocado con el {Origen}?"

comment.en: Request that checks which is the Argument/Action that has not been interpreter correctly, after a negative ReassureFeedbackRequest.

example.value:
"I have too many options taking into account the information you provided to me."

"I have too many options taking into account the information you provided to me."

"Tengo demasiadas opciones con la información que me has dado."

"Tengo demasiadas opciones con la información que me has dado."

comment.en: Response given when the alternatives (in general) are too big.

example.value:
¿En qué puedo ayudarte?

Dame tu comando.

How can I help you?

Tell me your command.

comment.en: Request to the user to provide their (initial) command.

example.value:
[Previous SysResp: "I couldn't resolve the action from your request".]
"Do you want to {ActionTag}?

"Do you want to {go somewhere}?

[Previous SysResp: "No he podido resolver la acción a partir de tu petición"]

"¿Quieres {ActionTag}?

"¿Quieres {que te lleve a algún sitio}?"

comment.en: Request that makes the user choose from a set of Actions obtained through inference.

comment.undefined: Element that is linked to a function in the Dialogue Manager code. This element also determines the implications of the output of said function in the code.
Step in the dialogue process that requires a system interaction with the user (SystemStep).

example.value:
The {Argument} is {Argument_value}, isn't it?

"The Destination is "Auditorium", isn't it?"

"El {Argument} es el {Argument_value}, ¿verdad?"

"El Destino es el "Auditorio", ¿verdad?"

comment.en: Request made to reassure the assignation of a value from the KEE to an Argument.

example.value: The item {item} can be associated to many arguments!
¡El item {item} puede asociarse a varios argumentos!

comment.en: Response that the system gives when an item can be associated to more than one argument.
Reponse given to the user when the UserResponse does not correspond with the expected response of the SystemRequest.
"I think I haven't understood. Can you be more specific?
comment.es: "Creo que no te he entendido. ¿Puedes ser un poco más concreto con tu respuesta?"

comment.en: The item {item} is not compatible with any argument for this action.
comment.es: El item {item} no es compatible con ningún argumento de la acción.
comment.undefined: The system informs the user the Item value provided is not compatible with any action argument, according to what has been modelled in the KB.

example.value: Do you want to go to the laboratory?

comment.en:
Request the response of which is expected to be limited to "Yes" or "No" (and equivalents).

Also known as "Polar question" in linguistics.

example.value: ¡Tu comando se puede asociar a demasiados elementos!
Your command can be associated to too many elements!

comment.en: Response given when the number of possible World Elements is too big.

example.value: I do not have more options to offer you!
¡No tengo más opciones que mostrarte!

comment.en: Response that the system displays when it runs out of options. It is intended to continue with a full request of the element that the previous options corresponded to.

example.value:
[Previous SysResponse: "This item cannot be {ArgTag}"]
"Can you verify?"

[Previous SysResponse: "This item cannot be {the destination}"]
"Can you verify?"

[PreviousSysResponse: "Este elemento no puede ser {ArgTag}"]
"¿Puedes verificarlo?"

[PreviousSysResponse: "Este elemento no puede ser {el destino}"]
"¿Puedes verificarlo?"

comment.en: Request that requires the user to repeat some information.

example.value: "Lo siento, no te he entendido. ¿Puedes repetir, por favor?
"I am sorry, but I haven't understood. Can you repeat, please?"

comment.en: Response that informs the user that the system has not understood the user command.

example.value:
"So, you want me {Action} {ArgumentConnector} {Argument}, right?"

"So, you want me {to take you} {to} {the toilet}, right?"

"Entonces, quieres que {Action} {ArgumentConnector} {Argument}, ¿verdad?"

"Entonces, quieres que {te lleve} {a} {l baño}, ¿verdad?"

comment.en: Request that is sent in order to obtain feedback whether the interpretation obtained is correct or not.

example.value:
Situation: the intent for the Request could be "Information" or "Guiding"

"¡Cuántas interpretaciones! ¡A ver si me puedes ayudar! ¿Quieres {Intent}?"
"¿Entonces necesitas {Intent}?

SYS: "¡Cuántas interpretaciones! ¡A ver si me puedes ayudar! ¿Quieres {que te dé información}?"

USR: "No"

SYS: "¿Entonces necesitas {que te lleve}?

USR: "Sí"

Situation: the Intent for the Request could be "Information" or "Guiding"

"So many interpretations! See if you can help me! Do you need {Intent}?"
"Then do you need {Intent}?


SYS: "So many interpretations! See if you can help me! Do you need {Information}?"

USR: "No"

SYS: "Then do you need {Guiding}?

USR: "Yes"

comment.en: Request made when a UserRequest can belong to different Intents. The strategy is asking for each Intent option until the user confirms.

example.value: ¡Tu comando se puede asociar a demasiadas acciones! ¿Puedes repetir y ser un poco más específico, por favor?
Your command can be associated to too many actions! Can you repeat and be more specific, please?

comment.en: Response given when the number of possible Actions is too big.

example.value:
"Con las características que me has dado, no he podido averiguar el {Argument}."

"Con las características que me has dado, no he podido averiguar el {Error}."

"I cannot guess the {Argument} with the information you provided."

"I cannot guess the {Error} with the information you provided."

comment.en: This would imply an ArgumentRequest/ArgumentCharacteristicRequest
